record_data.record_plain_text: AGREEMENT BETWEEN PHILADELPHIA ELECTRIC COMPANY AND PUBLIC SERVICE ELECTRIC AND GAS COMPANY DATED JANUARY 12, 1932 AGREEMENT BETWEEN PHILADELPHA ELECTRIC COMPANY AND PUBLIC SERVICE ELECTRIC AND GAS COMPANY Dated January 12, 1932 THIS AGREEMENT made and entered into this twelfth day of January 1932, by and between PHILADELPHIA ELECTRIC COMPANY, (successor to THE PHILADELPHIA ELECTRIC COMPANY and DELAWARE COUNTY ELECTRIC COMPANY) a corporation organized under the laws of the Commonwealth of COMPANY, a corporation organized under the laws of the State of N ew J ersey, hereinaft W I T N E S S E T H WHEREAS, PE has entered into an agreement with the Pennsylvania Railroad energy to PRR; and WHEREAS, PRR desires PE to supply energy under the said agreement dated July 21, 1927 for use on its electrified lines east of the Pennsylvania - New Jersey State Line, and PE is willing to supply such energy; and electrified system east of the Pennsylvania - New Jersey State Line, and its load in the City of Philadelphia and territory adjacent thereto, of which diversity PRR proposes to take advantage; and WHEREAS, PRR proposes to transmit to that portion of its transmission sy stem east of the Pennsylvania - New Jersey State Line, the said energy received from PE under the agreement dated July 21, 1927 over its own transmission circuits which are to be four 4/0 copper single phase 132,000 volt circuits or equivalent and will be of sufficient capacity to accomplish this purpose under normal conditions of operations; and WHEREAS, PRR desires to purchase from PE firm emergency power for that portion of its transmission system east of the Pennsylvania - New Jersey State Line , to protect the service of P R R in case of emergencies, and PE is willing to supply such firm emergency power; and WHEREAS, PE has entered into an agreement with PRR of even date herewith, supplementary to the said agreement dated July 21, 1927, for the supply of such firm emergency power; and WHEREAS, PE and PS with Pennsylvania Power and Light Company have installed a 220,000 volt interconnection ring over and by means of which the sixty (60) cycle transmission systems of the PE and PS are normally operated in paralle l; and WHEREAS, the Metuchen Switching Station of PS and the sixty (60) cycle transmission system of PS as interconnected with that of PE form the most practicable and economical means of transmitting and delivering such firm emergency power from the power sources of PE to PRR; and WHEREAS, PE desires PS to install in its Metuchen Switching Station and to operate and maintain for the benefit of PE suitable equipment for the transmission and delivery of firm emergency power from the system of PE to PRR, and to receive and transmit from the system of PE and deliver to PRR such firm emergency power as PRR may be entitled to demand from PE under the said agreement between PRR and PE of even date herewith, and PS is willing to render these services; and WHEREAS, PRR has entered into an agreement with PS of even date herewith substation and transmission lines on the site of the Metuchen Switching Station of PS; NOW, THEREFORE, the pa rties hereto each in consideration of the premises and of the promises of the other mutually convenant, promise and agree as follows: ARTICLE I CHARACTER OF SERVICE Sec. 1. Under the agreement between PRR and PE of even date herewith, PRR has agreed to no tify PE eighteen (18) months in advance of the date upon which PRR desires the installation of the motor - generator set for the supply of firm emergency power by PE in the amount of Twenty - Five Thousand (25,000) kilowatts, and that if prior notice has not been given, then the said agreement constitutes a notice as of January 1, 1933 of the desire of PRR for the supply of firm emergency power on July 1, 1934. Sec. 2. In event of PE receiving notice from PRR under the provisions recited in Section 1 of this Article, PE shall transmit such notice to PS immediately upon receipt thereof. Sec. 3. On, or as soon as practicable after July 1, 1934 or such earlier date as may be designated in written notice transmitted to P S in accordance with Section 2 of this Arti cle provided such notice shall be received by PS at least eighteen months prior to such earlier date, PS shall have completed the installation in its Metuchen Switching Station, including necessary building and structures, of one (1) Twenty - Five Thousand ( 25,000) kilowatt motor - generator set with solid coupling, either similar in type, overload rating and amount of auxiliary apparatus required, to those installed at Lamokin Substation of PE and with necessary switching equipment for the motor - generator set only similar to that installed at Lamokin Substation of PE, to be suitably connected to the 11,000 - volt windings of the two existing transformer banks at the Metuchen Switching Station and to be capable of operating in parallel with the supply equipment of PE at with one or more such circuits in service, during normal parallel operation of the 60 cycle transmission systems of PE and PS, or, if desired by either of the parties hereto, with an asynchronous motor substituted for the synchronous motor of the said motor - generator set. The field range and other mechanical performance of said motor - generator set, regulator and auxiliaries must be such as to comply with the voltage regulation requirements of PRR and be similar in extent to that provided by the apparatus of PE at Lamokin and also be adjustable for satisfactory operation in parallel with normal sources of supply of PE through the transmission lines of PRR. PE, due to its respons ibility to PRR under the said agreement of even date herewith, shall have the final authority in approving all plans and specifications relating to the installation of the aforesaid motor - generator set, building, structures and auxiliary apparatus, subject to arbitration in event of any disagreement arising therefrom. Sec. 4. It is mutually agreed that during the delivery and transmission of firm emergency power hereunder, the 60 cycle transmission systems of PE and PS shall be normally operated in parallel over the 220,000 volt or other interconnecting lines. Sec. 5 . Under its agreement with PS of even date herewith, PRR has arranged for transmission line on t he site of Metuchen Switching Station of PS. Under its agreement with PE of even date herewith, PRR has agreed to install, at its own expense, on the plot of ground made available by PS, suitable step - up transformer and switching equipment for receiving an d distributing the energy to be transmitted from the system of PE and delivered to PRR for the account of PE at this point, and to install, on its own right - of - way, transmission lines from its outdoor substation to the main transmission lines of PRR. Under the said agreement, PRR has further agreed to bear the entire cost of necessary inspection, repair and maintenance of its step - up transformer and switching equipment installed on the site of the Metuchen Switching Station of PS, and of its transmission li nes. Such step - up transformers, switching equipment and transmission lines shall remain the property of PRR at the termination of this agreement. In view of the installation of the aforementioned equipment of PRR at its Metuchen Switching Station, PS, wit hout charge to PRR, shall supply D.C. control outdoor substation in accordance with the directions of the authorized representatives of PRR, but such operation shall not include inspection, repair and maintenance. Sec. 6 . PS shall operate and maintain the motor - generator set and necessary equipment which it shall install in its Metuchen Switching Station under Section 3 of this Article, and shall control the supply f rom this motor - generator set to the transmission lines of PRR for the performance of the following functions: (a) For the purpose of transmitting and delivering firm power to PRR from the system of PE in emergencies arising either within the system of PRR or w ithin that of PE. Emergencies arising in the system of PRR under which PRR shall have the right to call upon PE for firm emergency power to be transmitted from the system of PE and delivered to PRR at Metuchen Switching Station by PS shall be understood t facilities or equipment sufficient in extent to prevent the successful transmission at operating voltage by PRR from the points of supply of PE to any portion of the Pennsylvania - New Jersey State Line, either of the normal demand of PRR on the said portion of its electrified system or of any abnormal demand which shall have been incurred in accordance with the provisions of Section 4 of Article I of the said agree ment between PE and PRR dated July 21, 1927. Upon notice from PE of emergencies arising in its system, PS shall receive and transmit from the system of PE and deliver to PRR from the motor - generator set and equipment to be installed under Section 3 of this Article, such portion of the normal demand of PRR upon PE as does not exceed the safe carrying capacity of the equipment . In either case, PE shall supply the energy required - corrected for transmission, transformation, and conversion losses from its own transmission system to the transmission system of PS and PS shall receive and transmit from the system of PE and transform, convert, and deliver to PRR such energy for the account of PE at Metuchen Switching Station, subject to the availability of the moto r - generator set and equipment to be installed hereunder. It is understood and agreed that said receipt, transmission, transformation, conversion and delivery by PS for account of PE may be in excess of Twenty - Five Thousand (25,000) kilowatts to the extent that the transmission and transformation facilities used by PS for its other services permit, without curtailing or jeopardizing such other services. PE shall supply to PS at each of the several interconnections between the parties hereto which may from time to time exist, such portion of the total amount of energy to be thus supplied as PS may from time to time direct, in so far as such direction by PS shall not impose unreasonable or impracticable conditions of delivery in the system of PE. (b) For the purp ose of utilizing the motor - generator set as a synchronous condenser. In accordance with instructions to be received from PE, PS shall operate the motor - generator set as a synchronous condenser, either on a definite daily schedule, at irregular intervals, or continuously, as my be desired. All energy losses in connection therewith shall be supplied by PRR during such operation through and from its own transmission circuits. Sec. 7. In event of non - parallel operation normally of the 60 cycle systems of PE and PS, causing interference with the reasonably prompt and effective delivery of firm emergency power, as provided for herein, PS agrees so to modify such motor - generator set and other equipment as to avoid such interference. Sec. 8. It is contemplated t hat the energy to be delivered to PRR hereunder will be transformed by means of the 11,000 - volt windings of the two existing transformer banks at the Metuchen Switching station of PS and that these transformer banks will be used also for the supply of the other services of PS. During the period that said method of transformation is utilized, it is understood and agreed that the receipt, transmission, transformation, conversion and delivery to PRR of energy hereunder shall be subject to the availability of spare capacity in the said existing transformer banks at the Metuchen Switching Station at the time that delivery of energy to PRR is called for hereunder. If, however, the load conditions become such that there is not sufficient capacity in the said trans former banks for transforming bo th the energy to be transformed, converted and delivered hereunder and the energy required for the other services of PS, and PE shall in writing notify PS of its desire for some other form of transformer capacity; or if PS s hall at some future time require the use of the said 11,000 - volt windings for its other services and shall in writing notify PE thereof; or if PE shall at any time deem the transformer capacity installed a the Metuchen Switching Station inadequate for the services to be rendered hereunder and shall in writing notify PS thereof; then PS shall provide at its Metuchen Switching Station in lieu of the said 11,000 - volt windings either: (a) One nominally 25,000 - kilovolt - ampere 132,000/11,000 - volt transformer bank cap able of transforming the rated capacity of the aforesaid motor - generator set, or (b) One nominally 80,000 - kilovolt - ampere 132,000/11,000/26,000 - volt transformer bank capable of transforming to 11,000 volts the rated capacity of the aforesaid motor - generator set (nominally 25,000 kilowatts) and simultaneously to 26,000 volts the rated capacity of one of the nominally 55,000 - kilovolt - ampere existing transformer banks at the Metuchen Switching Station, w hichever may be desired by PE, together with appurtenant fo undations, switches and other equipment. Whenever a transformer bank shall be provided by PS under the foregoing provisions of this Section, the payments hereinafter specified to be made by PE to PS monthly and at the termination hereof shall be increased by including therein equitable compensation to PS for providing, operating and maintaining the transformer bank and other facilities so provided and for their replacement, and all provisions of this agreement relating to the facilities specified in Sectio n 3 of Article 1 hereof shall relate in like manner to the transformer bank and other facilities so provided. ARTICLE II MEASUREMENT OF DEMAND AND ENERGY Sec. 1. As soon as practicable after the end of each month beginning with the date when the motor - gen erator set and necessary equipment installed under Section 3 of Article I hereof shall become ready or initial commercial operation, P S shall send to PE a statement of the quantity of energy and reactive power received and transmitted from the system of PE and delivered to PRR for the account of PE under this agreement during each even clock hour of that calendar month and during the calendar month. Sect. 2 . All electronic energy received and transmitted from the system of PE and delivered to PRR for the a ccount of PE under this agreement by PS shall be measured both as to maximum demand and as to kilowatt hours by meters on the 13,200 mold 25 cycle bus bars of the motor - generator set or sets to be installed by PS in its Metuchen Switching Station. Said me ters shall be installed, read and maintained by PS, shall be of a standard type and manufacture and shall accurately measure the energy received and transmitted from the system of PE and delivered to PRR by PS in electrical units and in periods of time as required by the terms of this agreement. PRR and PE shall have the right to be represented at the readings of these instruments and at the checking, adjustment or changing thereof. Sec. 3. All meters shall be tested and calibrated when necessary by compa rison with accurate standards, and if as the result of any test a meter shall be found incorrect or inaccurate, it shall be restored to an accurate condition or a new meter shall be substituted. In case PRR shall at any time believe that any meter registe rs incorrectly, PRR has agreed under its agreement with PE of even date herewith to make written request upon PE that a test be made of such meter. PE shall then make request in writing upon PS for such test. In case PE shall at any time believe that any meter registers incorrectly, PE shall make request in writing upon PS that a test be made of such meter. Whether the request for such test shall originate with PRR or with PE, PS shall thereupon test and calibrate such meter and if it shall be found ina ccurate, it shall be restored to an accurate condition or a new meter shall be substituted. Any meter tested and found to be not more than two per cent (2%) from normal shall be considered accurate. If as a result of any test, any meter shall be found to register in excess of two per cent (2%), either above or below normal, then the readings of such meter previously taken shall be corrected according to the percentage of inaccuracy so found, but no such correction, either in respect to maximum demand or ki lowatt hours received and transmitted from the system of PE and delivered to PRR by PS shall extend back beyond thirty (30) days previous to the day on which such inaccuracy shall be discovered by such test, and if during such previous thirty (30) days one or more prior tests shall have been made under the provisions hereof, then no such correction shall extend back beyond the date of the last of such prior tests. If a test of any meter shall be made at the request of PE with the result that such meter sha ll be found to register not in excess of tw o per cent (2%) either above or below, PE shall bear the expense of such test. The expense of all other tests shall be borne by PS. All meters shall be kept under seal. ARTICLE III RATES AND PAYMENTS Sec. 1. For each calendar month of the term hereof, commencing with the date the motor - generator set specified in Article I hereof shall first be made available for service hereunder, but in no event before the date on which the installation of the said m otor - generator set is required to be completed under the provisions of Section 3 of Article I hereof, PE shall pay to PS for readiness to receive, transmit and deliver firm emergency power in accordance with this agreement, for operating and maintaining as herein provided the said motor - generator set, including necessary building, structures, auxiliaries and metering equipment associated with the said motor - generator set, except as provided in Section 3 of Article II hereof, for operating the outdoor substa tion of PRR including any auxiliary services related thereto as provided herein, and for all other services required to be performed by PS hereunder in connection with the said motor - generator set, superseded by Paragraph # 1 of the Amended Service Agreeme nt 1/ 30 /02 , and in addition thereto PE shall reimburse PS for the cost of any renewals and replacements of the said motor - generator set, including necessary building, structures, auxiliaries and metering equipment associated with the said motor - generator s et, made by PS during such month. Sec. 2. Any payments by PS to other parties, incurred solely on account of transmission of energy hereunder, shall be borne by PE in addition to any other payments to be made by PE as specified herein. The cost of any mod ification of the motor - generator set and equipment under the provisions of Section 7 of Article I hereof shall be adjusted between the parties hereto in an equitable manner. Sec. 3. All payments for charges incurred under the provisions of this agreement shall be due and payable on the fifteenth day following the rendering of the bill therefor. In case PE shall dispute the correctness of any portion of a bill, it shall nevertheless make payment of the undisputed portion. When agreement has been reached as to the disputed portion, PE shall promptly pay the amount agreed on, with interest at the rate of six per cent (6%) per annum from the date on which it was originally due. ARTICLE IV MODIFICATION OF AGREEMENT Sec. 1. Under its agreement with PE of even date herewith, PRR has agreed to notify PE eighteen (18) months in advance of the date when it requires a second motor - generator set of similar size, characteristics and auxiliary equipment to that specified in Section 3 of Article I hereof for firm emerge ncy power supply to that portion of its electrified system east of the Pennsylvania - New Jersey State Line, provided that PRR at or before the giving of such notice agrees to extend the term of the agreement between PE and PRR dated July 21, 1927 to a date ten years from the date of availability for commercial service of the second motor - generator set, and provided also that PE and PRR have previously agreed upon the necessary of such second motor - generator set in relation to the total load requirements of P RR supplied by PE, and the monthly payment to be made by PRR for readiness to supply firm emergency power by the second motor - generator set. Immediately upon receipt of such notice, PE shall transmit such notification to PS. PS shall install, subject to t he agreement for compensation as hereinafter required by this Section, including necessary building and structure and step - down transformer capacity necessarily installed in order to supply power for the operation of the said motor - generator set, in its Me tuchen Switching Station , within eighteen (18) months from the receipt of notice be PSE from PE or as soon as practicable after the expiration of the said period of eighteen (18) months , a second Twenty - Five Thousand (25,000) kilowatt motor - generator set w ith solid coupling, either similar in type, overload rating, amount of auxiliary apparatus required to those installed at Lamokin Substation of PE and with necessary switching equipment for the motor - generator set and supply transformer connections only si milar to that installed at Lamokin Substation of PE, to be capable of 132,000 volt single phase transmission circuits with one or more such circuits in service, during norm al parallel operation of the 60 cycle transmission systems of PE and PS, or if desired by either of the parties hereto, with an asynchronous motor substituted for the synchronous motor of the said motor - generator set. PS shall operate and maintain the seco nd motor - generator set and its necessary equipment similarly to the first motor - generator set and its equipment. The said notice to PS for installation of the second motor - generator set and other equipment shall not, however, become affective unless and u ntil agreement shall be reached by the parties hereto with respect to the payments to be made by PE to PS therefor and in connection therewith and the payment to be made and other terms and conditions to be met at the termination hereof in connection with the said second motor - generator set and other equipment. Sec. 2. PRR has further agreed in its agreement with PE of even date herewith to install and maintain at its own expense the necessary step - up transformer and switching equipment for receiving and d istributing the energy to be transmitted and delivered to PRR from the system of PE by means of the second motor - generator set, and transmission lines from this outdoor substation to the main transmission lines of PRR. PS shall similarly operate the outdo or substation equipment installed by PRR for receiving and distributing the energy to be transmitted and delivered to PRR from the system of PE by means of the second motor - generator set. ARTICLE V EFFECTIVE DATE AND TERMINATION SUPERCEDED BY PARAGRAPH # 7 OF THE AMENDED SERVICE AGREEMENT DATED JANUARY 30, 2002 ARTICLE VI LIQUIDATION OF INVESTMENT UPON TERMINATION Sec. 1. In the event of termination of this agreement either as provided in Article V hereof or for any other cause, th e n PS shall permit PE to remove and PE shall remove at its own expense the motor - generator set and its auxiliary apparatus installed under Sec ti on 3 of Article I hereof, but not including building, structures, or such parts of the facilities associated with said motor - generator set and its auxiliary apparatus as may not be readily separable from the land, other buildings, structures and facilities owned by PS; and on the termination date h ereof PE shall pay to PS nine hundred sixty - one thousand one hundred thirty - eight dollars ($961,138) less the value to PS at said termination date of the building, structures, and other facilities installed by PS under Section 3 of Article I hereof and whi ch shall not be removed by PE as aforesaid, due consideration being given to the extent to which such facilities can be utilized by PS either then or thereafter and to the costs which would be incurred, either then or thereafter, by PS if such facilities w ere not available. In the event that PS shall have installed under Section 1 of Article IV hereof a second motor - generator set, including necessary building, structures, step - down transformer capacity, auxiliary apparatus and switching equipment for the mo tor - generator set only, the payment to be made and other terms and conditions to be met at the termination hereof in connection with the said second motor - generator set and othe r equipment shall be determined similarly to the payment to be made and other t erms and conditions to be met at the termination hereof in connection with the first motor - generator set and other equipment under this Section. In its agreement with PE of even date herewith, PRR has arranged that in the event that it terminates the agree ment dated July 21, 1927 between PRR and PE as provided therein, and/or the agreement of even date between PE and PRR except as provided in Article IX, Section 2 thereof, PRR will purchase from PE the motor - generator set or sets and auxiliary apparatus the n installed in the Metuchen Switching Station for the service of PRR, or alternatively PRR will pay to PE a sum of money to be agreed upon as representing a fair division as between PRR and PE of the original or replacement cost of the said substation equi pment and auxiliary apparatus, and in either event PRR will pay PE a sum of money to be agreed upon as representing a fair division as between PRR and PE, of the original or replacement cost of the substation building and structures for said motor - generato r set or sets and auxiliary apparatus and of the cost of the step - down transformer capacity of PS installed for the said motor - generator set or sets. ARTICLE VII ARBITRATION Sec. 1. If and whenever any dispute shall arise respecting the construction of this agreement or respecting the rights and duties or either party hereto, and the parties shall be unable to agree with respect to the matter or matters in dispute, the same s hall be submitted for determination to a Board of three Arbitrators chosen as herein provided. The party desiring arbitration shall give written notice to the other party setting forth in general terms the question or questions to be arbitrated and determ ined and the section or sections of this agreement under which the right of arbitration arises, and appointing an arbitrator. Within ten (10) days thereafter the party so notified shall appoint in writing a second arbitrator and shall give written notice o f such appointment to the party desiring arbitration; but if within said ten (10) days the said second arbitrator is not so appointed and notified to the party desiring arbitration, then the party desiring arbitration may make application to any Judge of t he United States Circuit Court of Appeals for the Third Circuit (or for any Federal Circuit hereafter created which shall include the C ity of Philadelphia, Pennsylvania) for the appointment of such second Arbitrator; and it is hereby agreed that the said J udge may appoint such second Arbitrator. The first Arbitrator and the second Arbitrator so appointed shall, within ten (10) days after the appointment of the latter, select a third Arbitrator, but if they shall fail to do so within said period of ten (10) days, either party may make applications to any Judge of said Court as aforesaid for the appointment of the third Arbitrator, and it is hereby agreed that the said Judge may appoint such third Arbitrator. Submission to a decision by arbitrators in the ma nner above provided is hereby declared to be a condition precedent to the bringing of any section or suit by either party hereto against the other on account of any matter within the terms of this Article. Sec. 2. The award of the Arbitrators shall be dra wn up in writing and signed by them or a majority of them. The decision of a majority shall in every case be final and conclusive as to the controversy submitted and shall be binding upon the parties, subject, however, to modification, correction, or vaca tion or to appeal as may at the time be provided by law. Sec. 3. The expense incident to arbitration shall be paid by the party against whom the award shall be made, or, in the event of a divided award, the same shall be apportioned and paid in such manne r as the Arbitrators shall direct. ARTICLE VIII LIABILITY Sec. 1. It is expressly agreed that PS shall not be held responsible or liable on account of failure to transmit and deliver all or any portion of the firm emergency power to the extent and in the manner provided herein or for any reduction or delay in such transmission and delivery caused by strike not due to the collusion of PS, or fire, civil or military authority, insurrection or riot, the action of the elements or by any other cause beyond its control; and, on the other hand, it is agreed that if, for any such cause, firm emergency power called for by PRR under the terms of its agreement with PE of even date herewith shall not be received and transmitted from the system of PE and delivered to PR R by PS, such failure shall entitle PE to a proportionate and equitable deduction from the charge made in accordance with Section 1 of Article III hereof for the month in which such failure occurred. Sec. 2. It is recognized that firm emergency power must be available to PRR whenever emergencies arise which entitle PRR to firm emergency power service, in order to make this agreement of value to PE. If, for any reason, failure of PS to receive and transmit from the system of PE and deliver to PRR such firm emergency power shall be then PE shall in writing notify PS thereof, specifying the reason for complaint and PS shall forthwith proceed to remedy the trouble. If t he trouble is not so remedied within thirty (30) days of the receipt of such notice by PS or such period as may be mutually agreed upon, PE may by notice in writing to PS cancel this agreement, such cancelation to take effect as soon thereafter as PE may b e able to arrange elsewhere for the necessary reception, transmission and delivery of firm emergency power for PRR and in the interim, PS shall, under all terms and conditions o f this agreement, continue to receive and transmit from the system of PE and de liver to PRR for a reasonable time the firm ments and PE shall state in said cancelation when the reception, transmission and delivery of firm emergency power under this agreement shall cease. ARTICLE IX SUCCESSOR S AND ASSIGNS This agreement shall inure to and bind the successors and assigns of the respective parties hereto but no assignment thereof shall be made by either party hereto without the written consent of the other, unless such assignment be made to a co mpany acquiring substantially all of this transmission and generating facilities of the assignor. IN WITNESS WHEREOF, the parties hereto have caused this agreement to be executed this twelfth day of January, 1932. FOR PHILADELPHIA ELECTRIC COMPANY M.L.& B. BY W.E. The October 21, 1982 Amendment is hereby amended by deleting the Readiness - to - serve : Monthly P ayments For period September 1, 2000 through August 31, 2001 $102,250 For period September 1, 2001 through August 31, 2002 $106,417 For period September 1, 2002 through August 31, 2003 $110,583 For period September 1, 2003 through August 31, 2004 $134,136 For period September 1, 2004 through August 31, 2005 $137,545 For period September 1, 2005 through August 31, 2006 $141,073 For period September 1, 2006 through August 31, 2007 $144,725 It is further agreed that the Parties shall be entitled to initiate renegotiation of the Monthly Payment amounts set forth above as follows: (i) Monthly Payment amounts for periods from September 1, 2000 through August 31, 2003 shall not be subject to renegotiation hereunder; (ii) Monthly Payments amounts for the periods from September 1, 2003 through August 31, 2007 shall be subject to renegotiation at the option of PSE&G or PECO by providing written notice to the other Party no later than January 1, 2003. In the event either Party exercises its optional right of renegotiation, PSE&G shall supply a cost of service proposal to PECO by no later than February 1, 2003. by Amtrak, as successor-in-interest to the Pennsylvania Railroad Company with respect to that January 12, 1932 agreement, in providing passenger rail service on the Northeast Corridor (the January 12, 1932 agreement referred to herein as the "PECO/PS 1932 agreement"); and WHEREAS, the Metuchen Switching Station of PSE&G and the sixty (60) cycle transmission system of PSE&G, as interconnected with that of PECO form the most practicable and economical means of transmitting energy from the PECO system to Amtrak's electrified system on the east side of the Pennsylvania-New Jersey state line ; and WHEREAS, conversion of the power is needed because Amtrak's trains operate at 25 cycles rather than at 60 cycles, which, by the date of the PECO/PS 1932 agreement had become the de facto standard in the United States for electric power transmission systems; and WHEREAS, PECO desires PSE&G to continue to operate and maintain for the benefit of PECO, at PSE&G's Metuchen Switching Station, suitable equipment for the transmission and delivery of firm power from the PECO system to Amtrak, and to receive and transmit from the PECO system, and deliver to Amtrak, such firm power as Amtrak may be entitled to demand be delivered by PECO under agreements between Amtrak and PECO, and PSE&G is willing to render these services; and WHEREAS, Amtrak entered into an agreement with PSE&G on January 12, 1932 for the use of the ground necessary and suitable for the erection of Amtrak's outdoor substation and transmission lines on the site of the PSE&G Metuchen Switching Station; and
WHEREAS, PSE&G constructed the necessary facilities to perform the services required under the PECO/PS 1932 agreement and commenced service; and WHEREAS, pursuant to a letter agreement dated October 21, 1982, the parties changed the rates payable under the agreement in order to take into account present-day financial conditions, as of 1982, and the expanded use of the Metuchen facilities that had been typical of recent years; and WHEREAS, such use had gone far beyond the emergency back-up supply originally intended in the 1932 Agreement; and WHEREAS, the October 21, 1982 letter agreement and the January 12, 1932 PECO/PS agreement (together, the "Amended 1932 Agreement") were filed with the Federal Energy Regulatory Commission ("FERC" or "Commission") on July 16, 1983, and were designated as PSE&G Tariff No. 111; and WHEREAS, PSE&G made a further filing of Tariff No. 111 with FERC on July 19, 1993, in Docket No. ER93-799-000, which was accepted by FERC via letter order issued August 31, 1993; WHEREAS, PSE&G undertook a significant overhaul of the operation of its transmission substations in the 1990s and greatly automated their operation; and WHEREAS, as a result, by the mid-1990s, continuous staffing of these facilities for the performance of most operations was no longer necessary; and WHEREAS, at most PSE&G substations, PSE&G was able to realize substantial savings by utilizing an "on call" system whereby personnel could perform multiple functions and generally were present at substation sites only on an as-needed basis; and
WHEREAS, because of the age and uniqueness of the Metuchen frequency converter, automation was more difficult; and WHEREAS, when the possibility of automating the frequency converter was discussed with PECO, it objected and advised that Amtrak wished to have operating personnel present on a 24-hour, 7-days-a-week basis; and WHEREAS, PSE&G thus continued to staff the Metuchen Substation on a continuous basis, which, by the mid-1990s, was almost entirely for the purpose of performing frequency conversion services for PECO; and WHEREAS, the rates for frequency conversion services under the 1982 contract amendment, however, were premised upon the manner in which the substation was operated in the 1980s when the performance of the frequency conversion service was a small part of the operators' duties; and WHEREAS, the rates for service under the 1982 contract amendment did not take account of increases in labor rates and other costs over the period following 1982; and WHEREAS, by letter dated July 8, 1999, PSE&G advised PECO that PSE&G was providing notice of termination of the Amended 1932 Agreement as of April 7, 2000 in accordance with applicable law; and WHEREAS, PECO disputed PSE&G's interpretation of the Amended 1932 Agreement, including PSE&G's entitlement to terminate the contractual relationship existing between the parties; and WHEREAS, discussions between PSE&G and PECO with respect to entering into a substitute or amended agreement for frequency conversion services occurred during the Spring and Summer of 2000; and
WHEREAS, at a meeting in PSE&G's offices on September 5, 2000, PECO and PSE&G reached a settlement in principle with respect to the main elements of their respective claims; and WHEREAS, in addition to the rates for services, elements of the settlement involved clarification of PSE&G's obligations, especially with respect to the term of the agreement and responsibility for maintenance and risk of loss, and the amortization and eventual elimination of a $961,138 liquidation payment that the Agreement obligated PECO to pay upon termination; and WHEREAS, therefore, PSE&G and PECO entered into a subsequent amended agreement dated as of January 30, 2002; and WHEREAS, on or about August 27, 2006, PSE&G advised PECO that the Amended 1932 Agreement was going to expire on August 31, 2007, in accordance with the terms of the Amended 1932 Agreement; and WHEREAS, on or about March 24, 2008, PSE&G, PECO, and Amtrak agreed that the Amended 1932 Agreement would be extended on a month-to-month basis to allow PSE&G and PECO to negotiate to extend the term of the Agreement; and WHEREAS, on or about December 22, 2009, PSE&G filed revisions to Tariff No.
111 that were accepted by FERC on February 17, 2010; and
WHEREAS, on or about March 24, 2016, PECO, Amtrak and PSE&G reached an agreement making revisions to the Amended 1932 Agreement regarding: (1) the demand figure used for the calculation of the Incidental Wheeling Charge and Losses; and (2) procedures regarding potential extension or termination of the Agreement during the period 2019 through 2021; and
WHEREAS, that agreement was filed with the Commission, as a further amendment to Tariff No. 111, on June 15, 2016, and the filing was accepted by the Commission on July 14, 2016; and WHERERAS, on or about October 10, 2017, PSE&G, PECO, and Amtrak entered into a letter agreement to further revise Tariff No. 111 to change the rates charged by PSE&G for the performance of frequency conversion services and transmission services; and WHEREAS, on October 16, 2017, PSE&G filed with the Commission such revisions to Tariff No. 111, in Docket No. ER18-79-000, and the revisions were accepted by the Commission on November 21, 2017, effective on July 1, 2017; and WHEREAS, those revisions set forth procedures to be followed in advance of the December 31, 2020 termination date of Tariff No. 111; and WHEREAS, PSE&G, PECO, and Amtrak entered into negotiations during 2020 regarding extension of the services currently being provided pursuant to Tariff No. 111; and WHEREAS, PSE&G, PECO, and Amtrak have reached agreements on the rates, terms, and conditions under which PSE&G will continue providing the services that are being provided pursuant to Tariff No. 111; NOW, THEREFORE, in consideration of the premises and the undertakings herein set forth, intending to be legally bound, and intending that this agreement shall wholly supersede the Amended 1932 Agreement as subsequently amended, PECO and PSE&G hereby agree as follows:

CHARACTER OF SERVICE Sec. 1. The field range and other mechanical performance of said motor-generator set, regulator, and auxiliaries must be such as to comply with the voltage regulation requirements of Amtrak and be similar in extent to that provided by the apparatus of PECO at Lamokin and also be adjustable for satisfactory operation in parallel with normal sources of supply of PECO through the transmission lines of Amtrak. Unless otherwise specified in this Agreement, PECO shall have the final authority in approving all plans and specifications relating to the ownership and operation of the aforesaid motor-generator set, building, structures and auxiliary apparatus, subject to arbitration in event of any disagreement arising therefrom.
Sec. 2. It is mutually agreed that during the delivery and transmission of firm power hereunder, the 60-cycle PECO and PSE&G transmission systems shall be normally operated in parallel over the 220,000 volt or other interconnecting lines. Sec. 3. Amtrak has arranged for the use of ground necessary and suitable for the erection of Amtrak's outdoor substation and transmission line on the site of the PSE&G Metuchen Switching Station. Amtrak has installed, at its own expense, on the plot of ground made available by PSE&G, suitable step-up transformer and switching equipment for receiving and distributing the energy to be transmitted from the PECO system and delivered to Amtrak for the account of PECO at this point, and to install, on its own right-of-way, transmission lines from its outdoor substation to the main transmission lines of Amtrak. Amtrak has further agreed to bear the entire cost of necessary inspection, repair, and maintenance of its step-up transformer and switching equipment installed on the site of the PSE&G Metuchen Switching Station, and of its transmission lines. Such step-up transformers, switching equipment, and transmission lines shall remain the property of Amtrak. In view of the installation of the aforementioned equipment of Amtrak at its Metuchen Switching Station, PSE&G, without charge to Amtrak, shall supply D.C. control current at this point for the control of Amtrak's switching equipment, and shall operate such outdoor substation in accordance with the directions of the authorized representatives of Amtrak, but such operation shall not include inspection, repair, or maintenance. Sec. 4. PSE&G shall operate and maintain the motor-generator set and necessary equipment that it has installed in its Metuchen Switching Station, and shall control the supply from this motor-generator set to the Amtrak transmission lines for the performance of the following functions.

It is understood and agreed that said receipt, transmission, transformation, conversion, and delivery by PSE&G for account of PECO may be in excess of Twenty-Five Thousand (25,000) kilowatts to the extent that the transmission and transformation facilities used by PSE&G for its other services permit, without curtailing or jeopardizing such other services. PECO shall supply to PSE&G at each of the several interconnections between the parties hereto that may from time to time exist, such portion of the total amount of energy to be thus supplied as PSE&G may from time to time direct, in so far as such direction by PSE&G shall not impose unreasonable or impracticable conditions of delivery in the system of PECO. (b) In accordance with instructions to be received from PECO, PSE&G shall operate the motor-generator set as a synchronous condenser, either on a definite daily schedule, at irregular intervals, or continuously, as may be desired. All energy losses in connection therewith shall be supplied by Amtrak during such operation through and from its own transmission circuits. Sec. 5. In the event normal non-parallel operation of the 60-cycle PECO and PSE&G systems causes interference with the reasonably prompt and effective delivery of
firm power, PSE&G agrees to modify such motor-generator set and other equipment so as to avoid such interference. Sec. 6. It is contemplated that the energy to be delivered to Amtrak hereunder will be transformed by means of the 11,000-volt windings of the two existing transformer banks at the Metuchen Switching station of PSE&G and that these transformer banks will be used also for the supply of the other services of PSE&G. Sec. 8. Nothing herein to the contrary withstanding, PSE&G and PECO agree that, other than the performance of maintenance and tests as described under Article 1, Section 7 hereof, PSE&G shall be under no obligation to repair or replace the motor-generator set or any related equipment installed at the Metuchen Switching Station under this agreement or any of the component parts of the motor-generator set or any related equipment installed at the Metuchen Switching Station under this agreement, except as set forth in this Article 1, Section 8. In the event PSE&G determines that a repair or replacement of any equipment is necessary or advisable for the performance of services under this agreement, it shall so advise PECO pursuant to the form of notice set forth in Appendix 2 hereto and shall provide PECO with a non-binding estimate of the cost of performing such repairs or replacements; provided, however, that PSE&G shall be entitled to perform such emergency repair or replacement work on the motor-generator set or other related equipment, without advance approval from PECO, as PSE&G deems to be necessary to prevent or limit imminent damage to equipment at the Metuchen Switching Station or to prevent injury or loss of life and PECO shall be responsible for the costs of such emergency work. Following the receipt
by PECO of notification by PSE&G of the need for repairs or replacements, PECO shall advise PSE&G pursuant to the form of notice set forth in Appendix 3 hereto whether to perform such repairs or replacements and, if PECO so desires, PECO and PSE&G shall thereafter enter into good faith negotiations in order to reach agreement in advance with respect to the cost of performing such repairs or replacements. Such good faith negotiations shall include Amtrak, and the agreement that sets forth the cost of, and the terms and conditions that shall govern, performing such repairs or replacements shall be an agreement between PSE&G and Amtrak. In the event PECO requests PSE&G to perform such repairs or replacements, and PSE&G performs the repairs or replacements provided for under the agreement between PSE&G and Amtrak, PSE&G shall bill PECO for the actual cost it incurs to perform the work, calculated as set forth in Article 1, Section 10 hereof, or the amount mutually agreed upon in advance for the performance of such work. PECO shall pay PSE&G the amount billed by PSE&G in accordance with Article III hereof and shall pay interest on any amount in arrears at a rate equal to the prime rate charged by JPMorgan Chase Bank, N.A., plus one percent (1%). PSE&G shall be under no obligation to commence the performance of any work prior to the receipt of proper authorizations from PECO and an executed agreement from Amtrak. Without limitation or enlargement of any other provision of this agreement, PECO agrees that PSE&G shall not be responsible for any loss or damage resulting from, or occurring in connection with, PECO's decision not to proceed with any repairs or replacements identified by PSE&G, and PECO hereby further agrees that it will indemnify and hold harmless PSE&G for any claim made by Amtrak or any other third party with respect thereto.
Sec. 9. PSE&G agrees that it shall provide around-the-clock operators, seven days a week, at the Metuchen Switching Station that will be responsible for operation of the motor-generator set during the term hereof. In the event a plan of full or partial automation is agreed upon, the parties will thereafter enter into good faith negotiations for the purpose of determining a rate for the performance of services provided by PSE&G hereunder after the installation of the new automation equipment. The modified rate for the performance of services shall provide for the recovery of the capital costs incurred by PSE&G in connection with the installation of any new equipment and shall reflect any savings realized by PSE&G as a result of any reduction in its cost of labor. Sec. 10. The costs for any work performed by PSE&G under Sections 7 and 8 of this Article 1 (other than maintenance and tests set forth in Appendix 1 hereto), unless an amount is agreed upon in advance for the performance of such work, shall be determined by PSE&G in accordance with the procedures used for assigning the costs of competitive services as required by Section 7(a)(2) of the New Jersey Electric Discount and Energy Competition Act or any successor provision. Such procedures shall comply with all legislative requirements and any regulatory policies of the New Jersey Board of Public Utilities then in effect for billing competitive services performed by PSE&G.
ARTICLE II
MEASUREMENT OF DEMAND AND ENERGY Sec. 1. As soon as practicable after the end of each month, PSE&G shall send to PECO a statement of the quantity of energy and reactive power received and transmitted from the system of PECO and delivered to Amtrak for the account of PECO under this
agreement during each even clock hour of that calendar month and during the calendar month. Sect. 2. All electric energy received and transmitted from the system of PECO and delivered to Amtrak for the account of PECO under this agreement by PSE&G shall be measured both as to maximum demand and as to kilowatt hours by meters on the 13,200- volt 25-cycle bus bars of the motor-generator set or sets to be installed by PSE&G in its Metuchen Switching Station. Said meters shall be installed, read and maintained by PSE&G, shall be of a standard type and manufacture, and shall accurately measure the energy delivered to Amtrak by PSE&G in electrical units and in periods of time as required by the terms of this agreement. Amtrak and PECO shall have the right, upon reasonable notice to PSE&G, to be represented at the readings of these instruments and at the checking, adjustment, or changing thereof. Sec. 3. All meters shall be tested and calibrated when necessary by comparison with accurate standards and if, as the result of any test, a meter shall be found incorrect or inaccurate, it shall be restored to an accurate condition or a new meter shall be substituted. In case Amtrak shall at any time believe that any meter registers incorrectly, Amtrak has agreed to make a written request to PECO that a test be made of such meter. PECO shall then make a request in writing to PSE&G for such test. In case PECO shall at any time believe that any meter registers incorrectly, PECO shall make a request in writing to PSE&G that a test be made of such meter. Whether the request for such test shall originate with Amtrak or with PECO, PSE&G shall test and calibrate such meter and if it shall be found inaccurate, PSE&G shall restore it to an accurate condition or install a new meter.
Any meter tested and found to be not more than two percent (2%) from normal shall be considered accurate. If as a result of any test, any meter shall be found to register in excess of two percent (2%), either above or below normal, then the readings of such meter previously taken shall be corrected according to the percentage of inaccuracy so found, but no such correction, either in respect to maximum demand or kilowatt hours delivered to Amtrak by PSE&G shall extend back beyond thirty (30) days previous to the day on which such inaccuracy shall be discovered by such test, and if during such previous thirty (30) days one or more prior tests shall have been made under the provisions hereof, then no such correction shall extend back beyond the date of the last of such prior tests. If a test of any meter shall be made at the request of PECO with the result that such meter shall be found to register not in excess of two percent (2%) either above or below, PECO shall bear the expense of such test. The expense of all other tests shall be borne by PSE&G. All meters shall be kept under seal. ARTICLE III
RATES AND PAYMENTS Sec. 1. For each calendar month of the term hereof, PECO shall pay to PSE&G for readiness to receive, transmit and deliver firm power in accordance with this agreement; for operating and maintaining as herein provided the said motor-generator set, including necessary building, structures, auxiliaries and metering equipment associated with the said motor-generator set; for operating the outdoor substation of Amtrak including any auxiliary service related thereto as provided herein; and for all other services required to be performed by PSE&G hereunder in connection with the said motor-generator set, the sum of the following:
(a) An Incidental Wheeling Charge that will be calculated annually, on or before December 20 of each year to become effective January 1 of the subsequent year, as the product of Quantity and Rate, which are defined as follows: i. Quantity: The transmission obligation for Metuchen, which shall be the average of Metuchen's monthly peak demands for the prior 12 months from June through May, times a Multiplier, where the Multiplier shall be 1.0 in 2021, and then 0.75 in 2022, and then escalating by 0.05 in each subsequent year until it reaches 1.0. ii. Rate: PSEG "Derived" Network Integration Transmission Service ("NITS") rate that applies to PSEG's retail customers as of January 1 of the year in which the Incidental Wheeling Charge will be assessed. (b) An Annual Operations and Maintenance ("O&M") Amount of $1.55 million will apply in 2021 with an escalation of $16,500 each year through 2030, subject to a fixed annual adjustment factor commencing January 1, 2031, if PECO elects the option to renew, and subject to PECO's decision, after consultation with Amtrak, to continue PSE&G personnel on-site at Metuchen on a full-time, around-the-clock basis. The fixed annual adjustment factor will be equal to the Consumer Price Index for Energy, as published by the Bureau of Labor Statistics. If PECO notifies PSE&G that Amtrak no longer requires PSE&G personnel on-site at Metuchen on a full-time, around-the-clock basis, or on any basis less than full-time and around-the-clock, the parties will negotiate in good faith to reduce the O&M Amount accordingly.
Sec. 2. All payments for charges incurred under the provisions of this agreement shall be due and payable on the fifteenth day following the rendering of the bill therefor. Sec. 3. In case PECO shall dispute the correctness of any portion of a bill, it shall nevertheless make payment of the undisputed portion. When agreement has been reached as to the disputed portion, PECO shall promptly pay the amount agreed on, with interest at the rate of six per cent (6%) per annum from the date on which it was originally due.
ARTICLE IV
EFFECTIVE DATE AND TERMINATION
This agreement shall become effective January 1, 2021 and shall remain in effect for a term extending until December 31, 2030. PECO may renew this agreement for an additional five-year term, from January 1, 2031 through December 31, 2035, provided PECO provides PSE&G with 12 months prior written notice of such extension. PSE&G shall at all times have the right, at its option, to declare PECO in breach and terminate this agreement for cause, in whole or in part, by written notice if PECO (a) becomes insolvent or makes a general assignment for the benefit of creditors, files or has filed against it a petition in bankruptcy, is adjudged bankrupt, or its affairs are placed in the hands of a receiver, trustee, or assignee for the benefit of creditors; (b) fails to comply with law or the instructions of PSE&G; and/or (c) materially violates any provision of this agreement. The termination of this agreement shall not be deemed to discharge either party of any
obligation, with respect to such party, arising under the agreement at or prior to the date of termination. Nothing herein to the contrary withstanding, PSE&G shall be entitled at any time in its sole discretion to file for a change in rates (including, without limitation, terms and conditions of service) under Section 205 of the FPA, and PSE&G shall be required to file with FERC for any termination of this Agreement prior to the end of its stated term, including for any reason set forth in this section. Nothing in this Agreement shall be construed to impair any rights that PECO and Amtrak may have to contest any such FERC filing.
ARTICLE V
LIQUIDATION OF INVESTMENT UPON TERMINATION Sec. 1. In the event of termination of this agreement either as provided in Article IV hereof or for any other cause, then PSE&G shall permit PECO to remove and PECO shall remove at its own expense the motor-generator set and its auxiliary apparatus installed under Section 1 of Article I hereof, but not including building, structures, or such parts of the facilities associated with said motor-generator set and its auxiliary apparatus as may not be readily separable from the land, other buildings, structures and facilities owned by PSE&G; and on the termination date hereof PECO shall pay to PSE&G the amount of one dollar ($1.00), due consideration being given to the extent to which such facilities can be utilized by PSE&G either then or thereafter and to the costs which would be incurred, either then or thereafter, by PSE&G if such facilities were not available.
ARTICLE VI
ARBITRATION Sec. 1. If and whenever any dispute shall arise respecting the construction of this agreement or respecting the rights and duties of either party hereto, and the parties shall be unable to agree with respect to the matter or matters in dispute, the same shall be submitted for determination to a Board of three Arbitrators chosen as herein provided. The party desiring arbitration shall give written notice to the other party setting forth in general terms the question or questions to be arbitrated and determined and the section or sections of this agreement under which the right of arbitration arises, and appointing an arbitrator. Within twenty (20) business days thereafter, the party so notified shall appoint in writing a second arbitrator and shall give written notice of such appointment to the party desiring arbitration; but if within said twenty (20) business days the said second arbitrator is not so appointed and notified to the party desiring arbitration, then the party desiring arbitration may make application to the American Arbitration Association ("AAA") for the appointment of such second Arbitrator; and it is hereby agreed that the AAA may appoint such second Arbitrator. The first Arbitrator and the second Arbitrator so appointed shall, within twenty (20) business days after the appointment of the latter, select a third Arbitrator, but if they shall fail to do so within said period of twenty business days, either party may make applications to the AAA as aforesaid for the appointment of the third Arbitrator, and it is hereby agreed that the AAA may appoint such third Arbitrator. Submission to a decision by arbitrators in the manner above provided is hereby declared to be a condition precedent
to the bringing of any action or suit by either party hereto against the other on account of any matter within the terms of this agreement. Sec. 2. The award of the Arbitrators shall be drawn up in writing and signed by them or a majority of them. The decision of a majority shall in every case be final and conclusive as to the controversy submitted and shall be binding upon the parties, subject, however, to modification, correction, or vacation or to appeal as may at the time be provided by law. Sec. 3.Each party shall bear its own expenses incident to the arbitration.
ARTICLE VII
LIABILITY Sec. 1. It is expressly agreed that PSE&G shall not be held responsible or liable on account of failure to transmit and deliver all or any portion of the firm power to the extent and in the manner provided herein or for any reduction or delay in such transmission and delivery caused by strike not due to the collusion of PSE&G, or fire, civil or military authority, insurrection or riot, the action of the elements or by any other cause beyond its control; and, on the other hand, it is agreed that if, for any such cause, PSE&G fails to transmit and deliver such power, such failure shall entitle PECO to a proportionate and equitable deduction from the charge made in accordance with Section 1 of Article III hereof for the month in which such failure occurred. Sec. 2. It is recognized that firm power must be available to Amtrak whenever requested by Amtrak in order to make this agreement of value to PECO. If, for any reason, failure of PSE&G to receive and transmit from the system of PECO and deliver to Amtrak such firm power shall be so frequent and of such duration as to interfere materially with Amtrak's operation of its lines, then PECO shall in writing notify PSE&G thereof,
specifying the reason for the complaint and PSE&G shall forthwith proceed to remedy the problem. If the problem is not so remedied by PSE&G within thirty (30) days of the receipt of such notice or such period as may be mutually agreed upon, PECO may by notice in writing to PSE&G terminate this agreement, such termination to take effect as soon thereafter as PECO may be able to arrange elsewhere for the necessary reception, transmission and delivery of firm power for Amtrak and in the interim, PSE&G shall, under all terms and conditions of this agreement, continue to receive and transmit from the system of PECO and deliver to Amtrak for a reasonable time the firm power necessary for Amtrak's requirements and PECO shall state in said cancelation when the reception, transmission, and delivery of firm power under this agreement shall cease. ARTICLE VIII
SUCCESSORS AND ASSIGNS
This agreement shall inure to and bind the successors and assigns of the respective parties hereto, but no assignment thereof shall be made by either party hereto without the written consent of the other, unless such assignment be made to a company acquiring substantially all of the transmission and generating facilities of the assignor.
